  <static seed="1361" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions09.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{1}{10} + \frac{11}{10}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{6}{5}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with the same denominator, we simply add up the numerators and keep the denominator unchanged.</p>
<p>The result is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{1}{10} + \frac{11}{10}
        \amp = \frac{1 + 11}{10} \\
        \amp = \frac{12}{10} \amp  \hbox{We can reduce this by dividing 2 into both the numerator and the denominator.
}\\
        \amp = \frac{6}{5} \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
</solution>
